I believe we all agree that the government deceived the American 
people. However, I think we need to think about why we, as a people, were 
so easily deceived. In the hundreds of accounts of vets' war experiences 
I've read, the vast majority make note of their total ignorance of 
Southeast Asia, and of Vietnamese history--not only those who went in during '65 
or '66 (when the US advisors had already been there for almost 10 
years), but after it was a major public issue. Very, very few Americans 
read the few books then available.
<p>
When Iraq invaded Kuwait, my daughter, then in high school, asked me, 
then a PhD candidate, what I thought. And I had to say, well, I don't 
know where Kuwait is, or what the issues are...and if I, one of the best 
educated in America, didn't know, what does that say about us as a culture.
<p>
I've taught college in California for 11 years, and I have consistently 
found that my students who are immigrants from Mexico (or anywhere, but 
I've had many from Mexico) are FAR more conversant with world history and 
world affairs than my American-born students.
<p>
