I was very interested by Renny's remark about ignorance.  As a college teacher, I, too, have seen the vast majority of my students with almost no knowledge of the wider world, and what's worse, no desire to learn.  But I've been thinking about this on a personal level.  
<p>
Jed's bio fascinated me; I can't imagine myself so committed at such an early age.  But I was not ignorant; my folks got both the afternoon and morning papers and I read both pretty completely every day.  We always watched the news on TV, often twice a day.  We debated various issues around the dinner table, including civil rights, though I don't remember much discussion about Vietnam.  When I enlisted, my folks were less than pleased; they wanted me to go to college.  They were especially displeased that I had joined the Marines.  At that point, we began to discuss 'Nam.  I remember a debate with my mom, her asking "Why are we there?" and me running to find that quote by Patrick Henry: "...my country, right or wrong, but my country.." in answer.  That did not strike her as sufficient.
<p>
So, I'm wondering if the problem is ignorance in a different sense, not in the "lack of information" sense, but in the sense of critically evaluating that information.
