I don't think something as complex as the war in Vietnam or US participation in it (two different things) has a single central truth. But I think there are some important truths that Americans rarely grapple with.
<p>
1. It was a civil war in Vietnam, which was rooted in anti-imperialism. Vietnam fought a nine-year war (1945-1954) for independence from France. The US largely financed France's efforts to keep Vietnam as a colony.
<p>
2. US participation was rooted in neo-colonialism, and cold war globalist thinking, which turned the Third World into a battlefield for conflict between the Superpowers. {By which I do not mean the US and USSR or China were directly fighting each other in Vietnam--they were not. Other than supplying munitions, Chinese and Soviet participation on the National Liberation Front (NLF) side was minimal.} What I mean is that the US policymakers conceived of a global battle against the spread of "world communism," which legitimated neocolonialism. Despite our nation's own beginnings in an anti-colonial revolution, we were unable to see Vietnam as following in our own footsteps. (The first sentence of Ho Chi Minh's August, 1945 Declaration of Independence is: "We hold these truths to be self-evident: that all men are created equal." The second sentence makes reference to the French Revolutionary declaration of the rights of man and the citizen. Ho goes on to point out that neither the US nor France means to extend those stirring and wonderful words to non-white peoples).
<p>
The war was not a mistake. It was not carried out with "good intentions" in the sense that the US meant to do the best possible thing for the Vietnamese nation. It was coldly carried out policy rooted in the US racism that says nonwhite peoples don't count. The Vietnamese communists called the Saigon government the "puppet government" and so it was.
<p>
The slaughter of more than 200,000 Iraquis comes out of exactly the same ideology, which is, in turn, the same ideology that allowed slavery, genocide against Native Americans, and the annexation of one-third of Mexico.
<p>
The US needs to face up to the horrors of its own past in order to create a more humanitarian future.
<p>
