Consider Truman's dilemma at the end of WWII.  The French are making 
noises about restoring their "colony" in Indochina (a much more racist 
view of things, in my opinion) and threatening to "go communist" if we 
didn't help them.  On the other hand, there's Ho Chi Minh, an avowed 
communist, making threatening noises about independence and having the 
gall to use some of our words to do it.  The choice to Truman is a 
no-brainer:  go with the French and contain those pesky communists.
<p>
Truman did not arrive at this position lightly or without thought; the 
USSR was a genuine threat, and he had the image of Munich hanging over 
his head if he sought some kind of rapproachment with the USSR.  This was 
the first step in the series of steps that brought us to 'Nam.
<p>
Now, what can we do to prevent similar errors?  I think we need an 
international body with some real teeth.  Look what happened when the 
World Court ruled against our Central American policies - we ignored 'em. 
We are currently holding the UN hostage by our refusal to pay dues.  
Until we have an international body that has the capability to "abolish 
slavery" (to use an analogy from your post), we aren't going to get very 
far.
