The postings of the first week made me very uneasy.  I felt I was 20 years old again amidst the controversies of the time, trying to find the core truth from every point of view and not knowing where to go with it.
<p>
The communist threat was very real to me as a child.  As the child of military parents, I lived in Japan in the early '50s and remember days when the gates to the US base had to be
closed against the protesters who waved red flags outside.  In school we had air raid drills as well as earthquake drills.  I saw the rubble of whole towns that had not yet been rebuilt from the war and the toys in the local village shops that were made of American beer cans.  
<p>
My father was in the medical service corps so I don't remember conflict about his being a soldier.  My mother was actively involved in learning Japanese culture and making Japanese friends.  Her brother had been killed in action over the Pacific.  When we
returned to the States in December of '56 (I was 10), all the news was about the Hungarian revolt, another indication that communism meant misery to human beings.  It was frightening to hear Krushchev say, "We will bury you."  In the mind of the child I was then, I saw him slam down his shoe on the table with one hand while his other hand was hovered over "the button" that could trigger mass destruction. (The amount of emotion that came to me when the Berlin Wall came down surprised me as an adult, but now I know it came from my background as a child.)
<p>
So I approached the Vietnam war with a sense that we were doing what we were
supposed to do.  And I came out of it still unclear about what our role was,
but knowing war "was not healthy for children....," etc.  How does one get to
that utopia we thought might be just around the corner if only people could
realize that we are all brothers and should work together?
<p>
We won't get there.  Not as long as children aren't having their basic physical and emotional needs met, for a starter.  And that's a tough one.  As adults, we have the ability to dialogue and broaden our understanding of diversity.  We have the need to order and classify to understand issues but, as has been demonstrated here, we can't overgeneralize about groups or their motives.  Listening to stories is important.  For example, I know a woman from Beijing who was forced to work the countryside in China during the Cultural Revolution because her father was an academic. Her love for her country remains strong even though she has chosen to raise her son in a foreign country.  
<p>
I do not have the scars of having been in combat.  I know I would have them if I had been in that position and they would be deeply embedded and influence the rest of my life.  Each of us has to make sense of what heredity and environment has combined to make of us and proceed from there.  It is a continual process.   My hope for the information age and the age of the global economy is that we will identify with aspects of other human beings in other cultures and pull the common threads together.
<p>
Thanks to each of you for the postings.  My worldview has been broadened by this exchange.
<p>
